All fresh clean project created with 'cocos create' fails after 
'cocos run -p android'. adb logcat returned log similar to 
[https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-js/issues/1288](https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-js/issues/1288)

```
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): FATAL EXCEPTION: main
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): Process: com.symplestudios.penguinwars, PID: 29440
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: dlopen failed: cannot locate symbol "atof" referenced by "libcocos2djs.so"...
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): at java.lang.Runtime.loadLibrary(Runtime.java:364)
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): at java.lang.System.loadLibrary(System.java:526)
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): at org.cocos2dx.lib.Cocos2dxActivity.onLoadNativeLibraries(Cocos2dxActivity.java:85)
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): at org.cocos2dx.lib.Cocos2dxActivity.onCreate(Cocos2dxActivity.java:99)
E/AndroidRuntime(29440): at android.app.Activity.performCreate(Activity.java:5600)
```

Using help from [http://discuss.cocos2d-x.org/t/need-help-android-app-crash-on-launch/18908](http://discuss.cocos2d-x.org/t/need-help-android-app-crash-on-launch/18908) I've added the implementations of missing methods (atoi, rand and srand) to my AppDelegate.cpp and now the empty project runs as it should (shows cocos logo on device)

I've used JS as language for generation, ndk r10 and latest sdk. In case someone else will need it, here's the code that helped

```
static u_long myNextRandom = 1;
double atof(const char *nptr)
{
    return (strtod(nptr, NULL));
}

int rand(void)
{
    return (int)((myNextRandom = (1103515245 * myNextRandom) + 12345) % ((u_long)RAND_MAX + 1));
}

void srand(u_int seed)
{
    myNextRandom = seed;
}
```

Device is Xiaomi mi3, android version is 4.4.4, cocos version 3.10. This nasty workaround seems to be a wrong way to solve the problem. Can someone look into it, please? Definitely I'm not the only one experiencing this kind of issues

Using cocos 3.10
I have an Sprite3D and after creation I add an Physics3DComponent, something like this:
Sprite3D \* sprite = Sprite3D::create("mode.c3b");
Physics3DRigidBodyDes rbDes; //fill data, mass, shape etc
auto physicsBody = Physics3DRigidBody::create(&rbDes);
auto physicsComponent = Physics3DComponent::create(physicsBody);
sprite -> addComponent(physicsComponent);
//sync the node with the physics and vice versa
physicsComponent->setSyncFlag(Physics3DComponent::PhysicsSyncFlag::NODE_AND_NODE);

And now when rotating the node on my update method it can not go further than 90º on the rotated axis
sprite ->setRotation3D(Vec3(0, sprite ->getRotation3D().y + 10 \* dt, 0));

This rotation issue happens also if using PhysicsSprite3D instead of adding the component to a Sprite3D

I believe the code is wrong for creating a look at matrix.
In Mat4.cpp, code in Mat4::createLookAt:

```
    dst->m[0] = xaxis.x;
    dst->m[1] = yaxis.x;
    dst->m[2] = zaxis.x;
    dst->m[3] = 0.0f;

    dst->m[4] = xaxis.y;
    dst->m[5] = yaxis.y;
    dst->m[6] = zaxis.y;
    dst->m[7] = 0.0f;

    dst->m[8] = xaxis.z;
    dst->m[9] = yaxis.z;
    dst->m[10] = zaxis.z;
    dst->m[11] = 0.0f;
```

should be 

```
    dst->m[0] = xaxis.x;
    dst->m[1] = xaxis.y;
    dst->m[2] = xaxis.z;
    dst->m[3] = 0.0f;

    dst->m[4] = yaxis.x;
    dst->m[5] = yaxis.y;
    dst->m[6] = yaxis.z;
    dst->m[7] = 0.0f;

    dst->m[8] = zaxis.x;
    dst->m[9] = zaxis.y;
    dst->m[10] = zaxis.z;
    dst->m[11] = 0.0f;
```

And I got the correct rotation after the modification.

